`crates/ctx-verify/tests/` is the behavioral contract for `ctx-verify`'s public output: both files exercise the same `FakeRunner` substitution point (keying canned `CommandOutcome`s off the first CLI arg, with missing/`None` entries producing `CheckError::ToolMissing`) so no test spawns a real subprocess. Together they pin down the crate's parsing of clippy's `compiler-message` JSON-lines format, FAIL-line and fmt-diff output, and the two rendering modes (terse text and `--json`) that consume those parsed diagnostics.

The two files split by layer, not by tool: `checks.rs` verifies the parser and orchestration layer — dedup rules for repeated/multi-line diagnostics, default line/file fallback, diagnostic capping/truncation counts, and status precedence (`Errored` > `Fail` > `Skipped`/`Pass`) in `Report::new`. `render.rs` verifies the CLI-facing formatting layer built on top of those reports — exact terse-mode string shapes, the `"… +N more"` truncation tail, and that terse output never leaks a `status` JSON key while `--json` always includes one. A change to `CheckReport`'s fields or Serialize impl, or to the real cargo/clippy JSON schema, must be reflected in both files' fixtures simultaneously since both hardcode the same wire shapes independently.

Cross-file invariant: any diagnostic-bearing report, real or synthesized (e.g. non-zero exit with unparseable stderr), must never present an empty diagnostics list — both layers assert this from their own side.